          <h2>How We Test Telescopes</h2>
          <p>Our telescope testing methodology emphasizes real-world performance over laboratory specifications. Each telescope undergoes systematic evaluation across multiple categories providing comprehensive assessment of strengths and limitations.</p>

          <h3>Optical Performance Testing</h3>
          <p>We evaluate optical quality through star tests examining in-focus and out-of-focus star images revealing optical aberrations invisible in casual use. Perfectly collimated telescopes show concentric diffraction rings; asymmetric patterns indicate optical problems. We test on standard targets: lunar craters revealing contrast and resolution; Jupiter's cloud bands and Great Red Spot testing fine detail and color accuracy; Saturn's Cassini Division and ring structure evaluating contrast; double stars (Epsilon Lyrae, Albireo) measuring resolution; and deep sky objects (Orion Nebula M42, Ring Nebula M57, Andromeda Galaxy M31) assessing light gathering and contrast.</p>

          <h3>Mount Stability and Tracking</h3>
          <p>Mount quality dramatically affects observing experience—the best optics become frustrating on unstable mounts. We evaluate: vibration damping at all magnifications (tap test showing how quickly oscillations settle); smooth motion in both axes without binding or jerky movement; ability to hold position without sagging; and for GoTo mounts, alignment accuracy and tracking precision over extended periods.</p>

          <h3>Ease of Use and Setup</h3>
          <p>Setup complexity determines whether telescope gets regular use or collects dust. We time complete setup from storage to first-light observing, evaluate finder scope quality and alignment ease, assess focus mechanism smoothness and precision, and test user manual clarity for various experience levels.</p>

          <h3>Build Quality and Longevity</h3>
          <p>We examine mechanical construction, material quality, fit and finish, and durability through extended use. Multi-year testing reveals which telescopes maintain collimation, which develop mechanical wear, and which prove reliable season after season.</p>
