          <h2>Budget Picks: $200-$400</h2>
          <p>Budget telescopes represent crucial entry points into astronomy, and wise choices in this range deliver genuinely impressive performance. The key: prioritizing aperture and stability over features and accessories. These recommendations maximize viewing capability while minimizing cost.</p>

          <h3>Best Overall Budget: Sky-Watcher Heritage 130P ($200-$250)</h3>
          <p>The Heritage 130P tabletop Dobsonian delivers extraordinary value through 130mm (5.1-inch) aperture in compact collapsible design. This Newtonian reflector on simple altitude-azimuth mount provides genuine deep sky capability revealing hundreds of Messier objects, impressive lunar detail, and satisfying planetary views despite modest cost.</p>

          <p><strong>Specifications:</strong> 130mm aperture, 650mm focal length, f/5 focal ratio, 5.1 lbs weight, included 25mm and 10mm eyepieces (26x and 65x), red dot finder, tabletop Dobsonian mount. The collapsible tube reduces storage length to just 14.5 inches—ideal for apartment dwellers and travelers.</p>

          <p><strong>Performance:</strong> The 5-inch aperture reveals Orion Nebula structure, Andromeda Galaxy core with hints of spiral arms under dark skies, Ring Nebula as distinct donut shape, and dozens of open/globular clusters. Lunar observing shows crisp crater detail with good contrast. Jupiter displays cloud bands clearly with four Galilean moons obvious; Saturn's rings separate distinctly with Cassini Division visible on steady nights. The fast f/5 focal ratio delivers wide 1.2° field of view ideal for large nebulae and star clusters.</p>

          <p><strong>Limitations:</strong> Tabletop mount requires stable table/platform at proper height—not suitable for ground-level use. Fast f/5 optics show mild coma (star distortion) at field edges. Spherical primary mirror exhibits some spherical aberration at high magnification. Collapsible tube occasionally requires collimation adjustment. Small focuser challenges accepting 2-inch eyepieces.</p>

          <p><strong>Best for:</strong> Budget-conscious beginners wanting serious aperture, apartment/condo dwellers with limited storage, travelers needing compact scope, families introducing children to astronomy, experienced observers seeking ultra-portable grab-and-go scope.</p>

