          <p><strong>Strengths:</strong> Rock-solid stability (13-lb weight prevents vibration), simple maintenance-free operation, excellent build quality with thick aluminum tube, smooth dual-axis motion, and included accessories adequate for getting started. The tabletop design works well on card tables, picnic tables, or car hoods. Many owners use for decades as portable secondary scope.</p>

          <p><strong>Best for:</strong> Families with children (stable and simple), beginners wanting zero-complication setup, lunar and planetary enthusiasts on budget, RV owners and campers, experienced observers wanting portable widefield scope.</p>

          <h3>Best Budget Refractor: Celestron AstroMaster 70AZ ($180-$220)</h3>
          <p>The AstroMaster 70AZ provides quality refractor experience at entry-level pricing. While 70mm aperture limits deep sky performance, this scope excels at lunar observation, bright planets, and double duty as terrestrial spotting scope for nature/wildlife viewing.</p>

          <p><strong>Specifications:</strong> 70mm aperture, 900mm focal length, f/12.9 focal ratio, aluminum full-tube mount on alt-azimuth tripod, included 20mm and 10mm eyepieces (45x and 90x), StarPointer red dot finder, slow-motion altitude control, accessory tray.</p>

          <p><strong>Performance:</strong> The long f/12.9 focal ratio delivers excellent planetary performance—sharp views of Jupiter's cloud bands and four moons, Saturn's rings and Cassini Division, Mars during opposition, and Venus phases. Lunar observation impresses with crisp crater detail and minimal chromatic aberration (color fringing). Double stars separate cleanly—Albireo's gold/blue contrast stunning. Deep sky limited to brightest objects—Orion Nebula, Pleiades, Andromeda core—but views respectable considering small aperture.</p>

          <p><strong>Dual-Purpose Advantage:</strong> Unlike pure astronomy telescopes, this refractor excels in terrestrial use. Use as 45x spotting scope for birdwatching, wildlife observation, or scenic viewing. Erect-image diagonal (sold separately, $25-$35) provides right-side-up images for daytime use.</p>

          <p><strong>Limitations:</strong> Small 70mm aperture limits deep sky performance severely—galaxies and nebulae remain faint or invisible. Tripod legs somewhat thin causing minor vibration at high power. Altitude slow-motion control helpful but azimuth lacks similar control. Plastic focuser adequate but not premium quality.</p>

          <p><strong>Best for:</strong> Beginners wanting refractor simplicity, those needing dual astronomy/terrestrial scope, lunar and planetary enthusiasts, observers with limited storage space, those prioritizing portability over maximum aperture.</p>

