          <h2>Understanding Telescope Specifications</h2>
          <p>Telescope specifications describe optical and mechanical characteristics affecting performance. Understanding these specifications enables informed comparisons and reveals marketing versus reality.</p>

          <h3>Aperture: The Critical Specification</h3>
          <p>Aperture—the diameter of the primary light-collecting element (objective lens for refractors, primary mirror for reflectors)—determines telescope's fundamental capability. Larger aperture gathers more light revealing fainter objects and enabling higher useful magnification. Aperture matters more than any other specification for deep sky observing. Expressed in millimeters (mm) or inches: 100mm = 3.9 inches, 150mm = 6 inches, 200mm = 8 inches. Light gathering increases with square of aperture diameter—8-inch telescope gathers 4x more light than 4-inch telescope (2² = 4).</p>

          <p><strong>Aperture Recommendations by Interest:</strong> Casual Moon/planet viewing—70-100mm adequate; Serious lunar/planetary observation—100-150mm minimum, 200mm+ optimal; Deep sky from suburban sites—150-200mm minimum, 250mm+ recommended; Deep sky from dark sites—100mm shows hundreds of objects, 200mm reveals thousands, 300mm+ for ultimate deep sky performance.</p>

          <h3>Focal Length and Focal Ratio</h3>
          <p>Focal length—the distance light travels from primary element to focus point—determines magnification when combined with eyepieces. Longer focal lengths provide higher magnification with given eyepiece but narrower field of view. Expressed in millimeters: typical ranges 400mm to 2000mm.</p>

          <p>Focal ratio (f-ratio or f-number) equals focal length divided by aperture: 1200mm focal length with 200mm aperture = f/6 (1200÷200=6). Focal ratio affects field of view, image brightness, and optical characteristics:</p>

          <ul>
            <li><strong>Fast (f/4 to f/5):</strong> Wide field of view ideal for large nebulae and clusters, brighter images at given magnification, but requires precise collimation and premium eyepieces to minimize coma (off-axis aberrations).</li>
            <li><strong>Medium (f/6 to f/8):</strong> Balanced performance for both deep sky and planetary observation, manageable coma with quality eyepieces, most versatile focal ratio.</li>
            <li><strong>Slow (f/10 to f/15):</strong> Narrow field of view, excellent for planetary observation and high magnification, minimal optical aberrations, compact tube length (especially in catadioptric designs).</li>
          </ul>

          <h3>Magnification Calculations and Limits</h3>
          <p>Magnification = Telescope Focal Length ÷ Eyepiece Focal Length. Example: 1200mm telescope with 10mm eyepiece provides 120x magnification (1200÷10=120). Changing eyepieces changes magnification—lower numbers provide higher power (6mm eyepiece produces 200x on same telescope).</p>

          <p><strong>Maximum Useful Magnification:</strong> Approximately 50x per inch of aperture (2x per millimeter). Exceeding this produces "empty magnification"—larger but dimmer, blurrier images. 6-inch telescope: 300x maximum; 8-inch: 400x maximum. Atmospheric seeing typically limits practical magnification to 150-250x regardless of aperture.</p>

          <p><strong>Minimum Useful Magnification:</strong> Approximately 3-4x per inch of aperture. Below this, exit pupil exceeds eye's dark-adapted pupil diameter (7mm) wasting light. 6-inch telescope: 20x minimum realistically; 8-inch: 25x minimum.</p>

          <p><strong>Optimal Magnification Ranges:</strong> Deep sky objects—50-100x providing brightness and field width; Lunar observation—50-150x revealing detail without excessive magnification; Planetary observation—150-300x (aperture and seeing permitting); Double stars—vary by separation, typically 100-200x.</p>

          <h3>Resolution and Rayleigh Limit</h3>
          <p>Theoretical resolution—the finest detail telescope can distinguish—depends on aperture. Rayleigh criterion formula: resolution (arc-seconds) = 138 ÷ aperture (mm). Examples: 100mm telescope resolves 1.38 arc-seconds; 200mm resolves 0.69 arc-seconds. Smaller numbers indicate finer resolution. Atmospheric seeing typically limits actual resolution to 1-2 arc-seconds regardless of aperture, explaining why massive amateur telescopes don't always show proportionally more planetary detail than moderate apertures.</p>

          <h3>Mount Types</h3>
          <p><strong>Dobsonian (Alt-Azimuth):</strong> Simple altitude-azimuth motion on rotating base. Advantages: intuitive operation, maximum stability per dollar, minimal setup. Disadvantages: requires constant adjustment compensating Earth's rotation, field rotation during long exposures (affects astrophotography).</p>

          <p><strong>Equatorial (EQ):</strong> One axis aligned with Earth's rotation enabling single-axis tracking. Advantages: compensates for Earth's rotation through single motion, enables long-exposure astrophotography, setting circles assist object location. Disadvantages: complex setup including polar alignment, heavier and more expensive than alt-azimuth for same load capacity, counterweights add bulk.</p>

          <p><strong>Fork Mount:</strong> Tube supported by fork arms enabling altitude motion. Typically computerized in modern designs. Advantages: compact design, no counterweights required, excellent for catadioptric telescopes. Disadvantages: limited to specific telescope designs, motorization typically required.</p>

          <h3>Optical Designs</h3>
          <p><strong>Refractor:</strong> Lens-based. Advantages: sealed tube, zero collimation, excellent contrast, durable. Disadvantages: expensive per inch of aperture, chromatic aberration (unless premium ED/APO designs), long tube length.</p>

          <p><strong>Newtonian Reflector:</strong> Mirror-based with secondary mirror. Advantages: excellent aperture per dollar, no chromatic aberration, suitable for DIY. Disadvantages: requires collimation, open tube admits dust/air currents, larger secondary mirrors reduce contrast slightly.</p>

          <p><strong>Schmidt-Cassegrain/Maksutov-Cassegrain:</strong> Catadioptric combining lenses and mirrors. Advantages: compact tube, long focal length, flat field for astrophotography. Disadvantages: expensive, requires occasional collimation, narrow field of view, slower thermal equilibrium.</p>
